# Determining setbacks on oddly shaped lots considerations

**Fig 17 Setbacks for oddly shaped lots**

## Key:
- Curb (solid line)
- Lot line (dashed line)
- Sidewalk (hatched rectangle)
- Required setbacks (outlined areas)
- Buildable area (shaded gray areas)

## Lot Configurations and Setback Rules:

### Lot A - Flag lot
- Rear yard setback applies
- Front lot line is closest and most parallel to street
- Front setback is 10' instead of 20'

### Lot B - Corner lot
- 16' setback requirement shown
- Street side setback is 10' instead of 18'

### Lot C - Substandard Corner lot
- Front lot line is shortest of the two frontages
- W frontage < 50'

### Lot D - Through lot
- Has setbacks on multiple sides due to street access

### Lot E - Wedge shaped lot
- Wedge shaped lots don't have rear lot lines
- The rear yard is determined by a 20' radius from intersection of side lot lines

### Lot F - Lot with more than 4 sides
- Rear lot line is farthest and most parallel to street
- Interior side yard designation shown

### Lot G - Lot with more than 4 sides
- Similar configuration to Lot F
- Shows rear yard and front yard designations

## Additional Notes:
- All lots show front yard, rear yard, and street relationships
- Sidewalks are indicated along street frontages
- Page number: 23
